+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01P64KiRZmZqhE82rYZEbdFY","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! I've successfully read all the requested files. Here's the complete contents:\n\n## TASK.md\n\n```markdown\n# Task Queue System\n\nBuild a fully-featured in-memory task queue system from scratch. The system should grow incrementally through 12 phases, each introducing new capabilities that build on the foundation laid by earlier phases.\n\n## Overview\n\nYour task queue should support adding tasks, processing them, and managing their lifecycle. Think of it like a simplified version of systems like Bull, BeeQueue, or Celery -- but entirely in-memory with no external dependencies.\n\nThe system evolves through 12 phases of increasing sophistication:\n\n1. **Basic queue** -- adding and processing tasks in order\n2. **Named queues** -- multiple independent queues\n3. **Priority** -- some tasks are more urgent than others\n4. **Delayed tasks** -- tasks that should wait before becoming available\n5. **Retry with backoff** -- automatic retry when tasks fail\n6. **Dead letter queue** -- permanent storage for repeatedly-failing tasks\n7. **Task dependencies** -- tasks that wait for other tasks to finish\n8. **Concurrency control** -- limiting how many tasks run at once\n9. **Progress and cancellation** -- tracking and aborting work\n10. **Recurring tasks** -- cron-like scheduled task creation\n11. **Middleware** -- intercepting and transforming tasks in a pipeline\n12. **Graceful shutdown** -- orderly wind-down of the system\n\nRead `phases/*.md` for detailed requirements for each phase.\n\n## Getting Started\n\n- Export your main API from `src/index.ts`\n- All implementation should live under `src/`\n- No external runtime dependencies allowed (dev dependencies are pre-installed)\n- Write your own tests as you go to verify your implementation\n\n## Validation\n\n```bash\nnpm run build   # TypeScript must compile\nnpm run lint    # No lint errors\n```\n\n## Tips\n\n- Later phases will force you to rethink early decisions. Design with extensibility in mind.\n- Tasks should have unique identifiers and track their lifecycle status.\n- Consider how features like priorities, delays, and dependencies interact with each other.\n```\n\n## package.json\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"bench-task-queue\",\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n  \"description\": \"Task queue marathon benchmark\",\n  \"type\": \"module\",\n  \"scripts\": {\n    \"build\": \"tsc\",\n    \"lint\": \"eslint src/\",\n    \"test\": \"vitest run\"\n  },\n  \"devDependencies\": {\n    \"@types/node\": \"^25.2.3\",\n    \"@typescript-eslint/eslint-plugin\": \"^7.0.0\",\n    \"@typescript-eslint/parser\": \"^7.0.0\",\n    \"eslint\": \"^8.56.0\",\n    \"typescript\": \"^5.4.0\",\n    \"@vitest/coverage-v8\": \"^2.0.0\",\n    \"vitest\": \"^2.0.0\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## tsconfig.json\n\n```json\n{\n  \"compilerOptions\": {\n    \"target\": \"ES2022\",\n    \"module\": \"Node16\",\n    \"moduleResolution\": \"Node16\",\n    \"outDir\": \"./dist\",\n    \"rootDir\": \"./src\",\n    \"strict\": true,\n    \"esModuleInterop\": true,\n    \"skipLibCheck\": true,\n    \"forceConsistentCasingInFileNames\": true,\n    \"resolveJsonModule\": true,\n    \"declaration\": true,\n    \"declarationMap\": true,\n    \"sourceMap\": true\n  },\n  \"include\": [\"src/**/*\"],\n  \"exclude\": [\"node_modules\", \"dist\", \"tests\"]\n}\n```\n\n## Phase Files\n\n### Phase 1: Basic FIFO Queue (/workspace/phases/phase-01.md)\n\n```markdown\n# Phase 1: Basic FIFO Queue\n\nImplement the core of the task queue: the ability to add tasks and retrieve them in first-in, first-out order.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- The queue should accept a payload (any data) when a task is added, and return a task object.\n- Each task must have a unique identifier (e.g., UUID), a status, and a creation timestamp.\n- New tasks start in a \"pending\" state.\n- Retrieving the next task should return the oldest pending task and transition it to a \"processing\" state.\n- If no tasks are available, retrieval should return `null`.\n- There should be a way to check how many tasks are waiting.\n```\n\n### Phase 2: Named Queues (/workspace/phases/phase-02.md)\n\n```markdown\n# Phase 2: Named Queues\n\nExtend the system to support multiple independent queues, each identified by a name.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Tasks are added to a specific named queue. If no name is given, a default queue is used.\n- Each named queue operates independently -- adding to one does not affect another.\n- Retrieving a task pulls from the specified queue only.\n- Creating a queue happens implicitly when a task is first added to it.\n- There should be a way to list all queue names that exist.\n- Asking for a task from a non-existent or empty queue returns `null`.\n- The API should remain backward-compatible with Phase 1 (omitting the queue name uses the default).\n```\n\n### Phase 3: Priority (/workspace/phases/phase-03.md)\n\n```markdown\n# Phase 3: Priority\n\nAdd priority support so that more urgent tasks are processed before less urgent ones.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Tasks can be assigned a priority level from 1 (highest) to 10 (lowest). The default priority is 5.\n- When retrieving the next task, higher-priority tasks (lower number) are returned first.\n- Tasks with the same priority are returned in FIFO order.\n- Invalid priority values (outside 1-10) should cause an error.\n- Priority operates per-queue -- each named queue maintains its own priority ordering.\n- The task object should expose its priority level.\n```\n\n### Phase 4: Delayed and Scheduled Tasks (/workspace/phases/phase-04.md)\n\n```markdown\n# Phase 4: Delayed and Scheduled Tasks\n\nAdd the ability to defer tasks so they only become available for processing after a specified time.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A task can be given a delay (in milliseconds) or a specific future time at which it becomes available.\n- Delayed tasks are added to the queue immediately but are not returned when retrieving until their availability time has passed.\n- Non-delayed tasks are always preferred over delayed tasks that are not yet available.\n- When multiple delayed tasks become available simultaneously, they should be ordered by availability time, then priority, then FIFO.\n- The task object should indicate when it becomes available.\n- Delays work correctly with named queues.\n```\n\n### Phase 5: Retry with Backoff (/workspace/phases/phase-05.md)\n\n```markdown\n# Phase 5: Retry with Backoff\n\nAdd automatic retry functionality so that failed tasks can be re-attempted with increasing delays.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- There should be a way to mark a processing task as completed or failed.\n- When a task fails and has retries remaining, it is automatically re-added to the queue with a delay.\n- The delay follows exponential backoff: `baseDelay * 2^(attempt - 1)` (e.g., 1s, 2s, 4s, ...).\n- The default maximum number of retries is 3, but this should be configurable per task.\n- The base backoff delay defaults to 1000ms but should be configurable per task.\n- The task should track how many times it has been attempted.\n- Retried tasks keep their original queue and priority.\n- If all retries are exhausted, the task remains in a failed state.\n```\n\n### Phase 6: Dead Letter Queue (/workspace/phases/phase-06.md)\n\n```markdown\n# Phase 6: Dead Letter Queue\n\nAdd a dead letter queue (DLQ) to capture tasks that have permanently failed after exhausting all retries.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- When a task has no more retries left, it is automatically moved to a dead letter queue associated with its original queue.\n- There should be a way to view all dead-lettered tasks for a given queue.\n- Dead-lettered tasks should retain their error information and a count of how many times they failed.\n- It should be possible to move a dead-lettered task back to its original queue for a fresh round of retries.\n- There should be a way to clear all dead-lettered tasks for a queue.\n- Each named queue has its own independent dead letter queue.\n```\n\n### Phase 7: Task Dependencies (/workspace/phases/phase-07.md)\n\n```markdown\n# Phase 7: Task Dependencies\n\nAdd the ability for tasks to declare dependencies on other tasks, so they only become available once their prerequisites are done.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- When adding a task, you can specify a list of task IDs that must complete before this task becomes available.\n- A task with unresolved dependencies is blocked and will not be returned when retrieving.\n- When a dependency completes, the system should check whether any blocked tasks are now unblocked.\n- Circular dependencies (direct or indirect) must be detected and rejected at task-creation time.\n- Depending on a non-existent task should cause an error.\n- A failed dependency does NOT automatically fail its dependents -- they remain blocked.\n- There should be a way to inspect a task's dependency status.\n```\n\n### Phase 8: Concurrency Control (/workspace/phases/phase-08.md)\n\n```markdown\n# Phase 8: Concurrency Control\n\nAdd per-queue limits on how many tasks can be processed at the same time.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Each queue can have a maximum concurrency setting that limits how many tasks can be in a processing state simultaneously.\n- If the concurrency limit is reached, retrieving a task returns `null` even if pending tasks are available.\n- Completing or failing a task frees up a concurrency slot.\n- By default, queues have no concurrency limit (unlimited).\n- There should be a way to set and query the concurrency limit and current active count for a queue.\n- Concurrency interacts correctly with priority ordering -- the highest-priority available task is still chosen, subject to the concurrency limit.\n```\n\n### Phase 9: Progress Tracking and Cancellation (/workspace/phases/phase-09.md)\n\n```markdown\n# Phase 9: Progress Tracking and Cancellation\n\nAdd the ability to report progress on running tasks and to cancel tasks.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A processing task can report its progress as a percentage (0-100) with an optional message.\n- There should be a way to query a task's current progress.\n- Listeners can subscribe to progress updates for a task and receive notifications when progress changes.\n- Subscriptions should be cancellable (unsubscribe).\n- Tasks in pending or processing state can be cancelled.\n- Cancelled pending tasks are removed from the queue and will not be returned.\n- Cancelled processing tasks have their status updated accordingly.\n- Cancelled tasks are never retried, even if they had retries remaining.\n```\n\n### Phase 10: Recurring Tasks (/workspace/phases/phase-10.md)\n\n```markdown\n# Phase 10: Recurring Tasks\n\nAdd the ability to schedule tasks that recur on a regular interval using simple cron-like expressions.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A schedule associates a cron expression with a queue and a task template (the payload to use each time).\n- Support a simple subset of cron expressions:\n  - `*/N * * * *` -- every N minutes\n  - `0 * * * *` -- every hour on the hour\n  - `0 0 * * *` -- every day at midnight\n- There should be a way to create, remove, and list active schedules.\n- A manual \"tick\" or \"check\" mechanism should evaluate all active schedules and enqueue tasks for any that are due. This is used for testing.\n- Once enqueued, recurring tasks are regular tasks subject to all other queue rules.\n- Removing a schedule stops future occurrences from being created.\n```\n\n### Phase 11: Middleware Pipeline (/workspace/phases/phase-11.md)\n\n```markdown\n# Phase 11: Middleware Pipeline\n\nAdd a middleware system that can intercept and transform tasks as they are processed.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Middleware functions can be registered per queue.\n- When a task is processed, it passes through all registered middleware in order before reaching the final handler.\n- Each middleware receives the task and a \"next\" function. Calling \"next\" passes control to the next middleware (or the handler).\n- If a middleware does NOT call \"next\", the task processing is skipped.\n- Middleware can modify the task (e.g., adding metadata or transforming the payload).\n- If a middleware throws an error, the task should be marked as failed.\n- A processing function/handler can be registered per queue. It is invoked after all middleware have run.\n- Each queue has its own independent middleware stack.\n```\n\n### Phase 12: Graceful Shutdown (/workspace/phases/phase-12.md)\n\n```markdown\n# Phase 12: Graceful Shutdown\n\nAdd the ability to shut down the task queue system in an orderly fashion.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A shutdown operation should signal the system to stop accepting new tasks.\n- After shutdown is initiated, attempting to add new tasks should produce an error.\n- The shutdown should wait for all currently-processing tasks to finish, up to a configurable timeout.\n- If processing tasks do not complete within the timeout, they should be force-cancelled.\n- Callbacks can be registered to run during the shutdown process.\n- The shutdown should produce a summary indicating how many tasks completed, how many were force-cancelled, and how long the shutdown took.\n- Calling shutdown multiple times should be safe and return the same result.\n- If no tasks are processing, shutdown should complete immediately.\n```\n\n## src/ Directory\n\nThe `/workspace/src/` directory is currently empty except for a `.gitkeep` file. There are no existing source files to display."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a02ec8d (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 19666\ntool_uses: 18\nduration_ms: 32215</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4d41520d-00c6-4a20-9375-7ce9d900f299","uuid":"5178661c-d4b3-451e-b75a-bdd04cb909c3","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Read all files in the /workspace/phases/ dir